04489nam a22005895i 9780774850896DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072004xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748508967 a10.59962/97807748508962doi  a(DE-B1597)662251  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE4410b.M36 2004eb 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a342.7108/51 aManfredi, Christopher P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFeminist Activism in the Supreme Court :bLegal Mobilization and the Women's Legal Education and Action Fund /cChristopher P. Manfredi. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b21 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tLegal Doctrine, Legal Mobilization, and LEAF -- tThe Path to Substantive Equality -- tGaining Ground -- tFamily Matters: Breakdowns and Benefits -- tA Difficult Dialogue -- tMaking a Difference: The Policy Consequences of Legal Mobilization -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tCases Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince 1980, the Canadian women's movement has been an active participant in constitutional politics and Charter litigation. This book, through its focus on the Women's Legal Education and Action Fund (LEAF), presents a compelling examination of how Canadian feminists became key actors in developing the constitutional doctrine of equality, and how they mobilized that doctrine to support the movement's policy agenda. The case of LEAF, an organization that had as its goal the use of Charter litigation to influence legal rules and public policy, provides rich ground for Manfredi's keen analysis of legal mobilization. In a multitude of areas such as abortion, pornography, sexual assault, family law, and gay and lesbian rights, LEAF has intervened before the Supreme Court to bring its understanding of equality to bear on legal policy development. This study offers a deft examination of LEAF's arguments and seeks to understand how they affected the Court's consideration of the issues. Perhaps most importantly, it also contemplates the longterm effects of the mobilization, and considers the social impact of the legal doctrine that has emerged from LEAF cases. A major contribution to law and society studies, Feminist Activism in the Supreme Court is unparalleled in its analysis of legal mobilization as an effective strategy for social movements. It will be widely read and welcomed by legal scholars, political scientists, lawyers, feminists, and activists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConstitutional historyzCanada. 0aEquality before the lawzCanada. 0aFeminismzCanada. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485089640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850896423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850896/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles